<P>
 McDonnell Settles Pollution Suit: McDonnell Douglas Corp. agreed to install 
$600,000 in air-pollution-control technology at its Long Beach and Huntington 
Beach plants to settle a lawsuit brought by state authorities alleging that the 
company failed to warn the public about toxic emissions at the sites. Under the 
proposed settlement filed in Los Angeles County Superior Court, the St. 
Louis-based company also agreed to pay $125,000 in penalties and other costs, 
California Atty. Gen. Daniel E. Lungren said. The suit stemmed from Proposition 
65, which requires companies to "provide a clear and reasonable warning" before 
potentially exposing the public to dangerous emissions, Lungren said. 
